04856nam a22007455i 9780813564494DE-B159720210107041344.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210107t20162016nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2016003240  a97808135644947 a10.36019/97808135644942doi  a(DE-B1597)526345  a(OCoLC)957619247  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ00aPN1995.9.C45bW58 2016 7aPER0000002bisacsh1 aWojcik, Pamela Robertson, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFantasies of Neglect :bImagining the Urban Child in American Film and Fiction /cPamela Robertson Wojcik. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2016] 4cÂ©2016  a1 online resource (256 p.) :b22 photographs  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aRutgers Series in Childhood Studies00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Mapping The Urban Child -- t1. Boys, Movies, And City Streets; Or, The Dead End Kids As Modernists -- t2. Shirley Temple As Streetwalker: Girls, Streets, And Encounters With Men -- t3. Neglect At Home: Rejecting Mothers And Middle-Class Kids -- t4. "The Odds Are Against Him": Archives Of Unhappiness Among Black Urban Boys -- t5. Helicopters And Catastrophes: The Failure To Neglect And Neglect As Failure -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAbout The Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn our current era of helicopter parenting and stranger danger, an unaccompanied child wandering through the city might commonly be viewed as a victim of abuse and neglect. However, from the early twentieth century to the present day, countless books and films have portrayed the solitary exploration of urban spaces as a source of empowerment and delight for children. Fantasies of Neglect explains how this trope of the self-sufficient, mobile urban child originated and considers why it persists, even as it goes against the grain of social reality. Drawing from a wide range of films, children's books, adult novels, and sociological texts, Pamela Robertson Wojcik investigates how cities have simultaneously been demonized as dangerous spaces unfit for children and romanticized as wondrous playgrounds that foster a kid's independence and imagination. Charting the development of free-range urban child characters from Little Orphan Annie to Harriet the Spy to Hugo Cabret, and from Shirley Temple to the Dead End Kids, she considers the ongoing dialogue between these fictional representations and shifting discourses on the freedom and neglect of children. While tracking the general concerns Americans have expressed regarding the abstract figure of the child, the book also examines the varied attitudes toward specific types of urban children-girls and boys, blacks and whites, rich kids and poor ones, loners and neighborhood gangs. Through this diverse selection of sources, Fantasies of Neglect presents a nuanced chronicle of how notions of American urbanism and American childhood have grown up together.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Jan 2021) 0aAmerican fictiony20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aCity and town life in literature. 0aCity and town life in motion pictures. 0aCity children in literature. 0aCity children in motion pictures. 0aMotion pictureszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP eBook-Package 2016z978311066614440uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978081356449440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813564494423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813564494.jpg  a978-3-11-066614-4  RUP eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEB